        -:   29:/** \class CwiseNullaryOp
        -:   30:  * \ingroup Core_Module
        -:   31:  *
        -:   32:  * \brief Generic expression of a matrix where all coefficients are defined by a functor
        -:   33:  *
        -:   34:  * \tparam NullaryOp template functor implementing the operator
        -:   35:  * \tparam PlainObjectType the underlying plain matrix/array type
        -:   36:  *
        -:   37:  * This class represents an expression of a generic nullary operator.
        -:   38:  * It is the return type of the Ones(), Zero(), Constant(), Identity() and Random() methods,
        -:   39:  * and most of the time this is the only way it is used.
        -:   40:  *
        -:   41:  * However, if you want to write a function returning such an expression, you
        -:   42:  * will need to use this class.
        -:   43:  *
        -:   44:  * The functor NullaryOp must expose one of the following method:
        -:   45:    <table class="manual">
        -:   46:    <tr            ><td>\c operator()() </td><td>if the procedural generation does not depend on the coefficient entries (e.g., random numbers)</td></tr>
        -:   47:    <tr class="alt"><td>\c operator()(Index i)</td><td>if the procedural generation makes sense for vectors only and that it depends on the coefficient index \c i (e.g., linspace) </td></tr>
        -:   48:    <tr            ><td>\c operator()(Index i,Index j)</td><td>if the procedural generation depends on the matrix coordinates \c i, \c j (e.g., to generate a checkerboard with 0 and 1)</td></tr>
        -:   49:    </table>
        -:   50:  * It is also possible to expose the last two operators if the generation makes sense for matrices but can be optimized for vectors.
        -:   51:  *
        -:   52:  * See DenseBase::NullaryExpr(Index,const CustomNullaryOp&) for an example binding
        -:   53:  * C++11 random number generators.
        -:   54:  *
        -:   55:  * A nullary expression can also be used to implement custom sophisticated matrix manipulations
        -:   56:  * that cannot be covered by the existing set of natively supported matrix manipulations.
        -:   57:  * See this \ref TopicCustomizing_NullaryExpr "page" for some examples and additional explanations
        -:   58:  * on the behavior of CwiseNullaryOp.
        -:   59:  *
        -:   60:  * \sa class CwiseUnaryOp, class CwiseBinaryOp, DenseBase::NullaryExpr
        -:   61:  */
        -:   62:template<typename NullaryOp, typename PlainObjectType>
        -:   63:class CwiseNullaryOp : public internal::dense_xpr_base< CwiseNullaryOp<NullaryOp, PlainObjectType> >::type, internal::no_assignment_operator
